  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can you locate the name of a proxy server?",
  "response": "Locating the name or address of a proxy server can vary based on your operating system and network setup. Here are several methods to find the proxy server details:\n\n### For Windows:\n\n1. **Network Settings:**\n   - Open the **Control Panel**.\n   - Go to **Network and Internet**.\n   - Click on **Internet Options** (you may need to switch to \u201cSmall icons\u201d view).\n   - In the Internet Properties window, go to the **Connections** tab, and click on **LAN settings**. This will show you if a proxy server is being used and display its address.\n\n2. **Command Prompt:**\n   - Open the **Command Prompt**.\n   - Type `netsh winhttp show proxy` and press Enter. This will display the current proxy configuration for the system.\n\n### For macOS:\n\n1. **System Preferences:**\n   - Open **System Preferences**.\n   - Click on **Network**.\n   - Select your active network connection (e.g., Wi-Fi or Ethernet).\n   - Click on **Advanced**, then go to the **Proxies** tab. Here, you can see the proxy settings, including the name or IP address of the proxy server.\n\n### For Linux:\n\n1. **Network Settings:**\n   - Go to `Settings` and find **Network**.\n   - Select your active network connection.\n   - Look for a section called **Proxy**; this should display your proxy server details if configured.\n\n2. **Terminal (Shell Command):**\n   - If you use terminal environment variables, check for proxy settings using:\n     ```bash\n     echo $http_proxy\n     echo $https_proxy\n     ```\n\n### For Browsers:\n\n1. **Google Chrome:**\n   - Go to Settings, then under 'Advanced', find the **System** section and click on **Open your computer's proxy settings**.\n\n2. **Mozilla Firefox:**\n   - In Firefox, go to Options, scroll down to the **Network Settings** section at the bottom, and click on **Settings**. This will show you the proxy settings specific to Firefox.\n\n### Using Environment Variables:\n\nIn some cases, proxy settings can be defined as environment variables. You can check these on both Windows and Unix-like systems:\n\n- **Windows:** Use `echo %HTTP_PROXY%` and `echo %HTTPS_PROXY%` in Command Prompt.\n- **Linux/Mac:** Use `echo $http_proxy` and `echo $https_proxy` in the terminal.\n\n### Additional Tools:\nIf you're part of a larger network (like a corporate environment), you might want to check with your IT department or network administrators. They can provide you with information about the proxy server you're required to use.\n\n### Conclusion:\nThe method you use will depend on your operating system and how the proxy settings have been configured. If you\u2019re having trouble, checking with your network administrator can often provide the quickest answer.",
